excerpt: Landmark group of 3 mixed-use skyscrapers designed to resemble flames, with evening light shows.
detail_description: Perched on a hill overlooking the Caspian Sea, Flame Towers in Baku is a striking trio of skyscrapers that pay homage to Azerbaijan's ancient reverence for fire. These iconic glass high rises, ranging from 36 to 39 stories, are designed to resemble flames and can be spotted from various vantage points across the city. The towers' evening light shows create a mesmerizing spectacle, evoking dancing tongues of flame against the night sky.
name: Flame Towers

excerpt: Museum with an emphasis on the art of carpet weaving, plus Azeri ceramics & costumes.
detail_description: The Azerbaijan Carpet Museum is a cultural institution in Baku that showcases the art of carpet weaving, Azeri ceramics, and costumes. Established in 2009, it features an extensive collection of Western modernists like Picasso and Chagall, as well as avant-garde works from Azerbaijan. Situated near the Caspian Sea on a sunny boulevard, the museum's unique rug-shaped architecture makes it a prominent landmark.
name: Azerbaijan Carpet Museum

excerpt: Spacious, modern building housing an auditorium, an art gallery & a Heydar Aliyev museum.
detail_description: The Heydar Aliyev Centre in Baku is a modern and spacious cultural complex that includes an auditorium, art gallery, and museum dedicated to the country's former president. Designed by the late Dame Zaha Hadid, this architectural marvel features soaring white curves and a timber-lined concert hall. Despite its controversial political associations, it has garnered international acclaim for its design and won the Design of the Year award in 2014.
name: Heydar Aliyev Center

excerpt: Restored 15th-century palace complex with a mosque, burial vaults & artifact & relic displays.
detail_description: The Palace of the Shirvanshahs is a 15th-century palace complex located in the Inner City of Baku, Azerbaijan. It is part of the UNESCO World Heritage List and considered one of Azerbaijan's architectural gems. The complex includes a main building, burial vaults, a mosque with a minaret, and other structures like a mausoleum and bathhouse remnants.
name: Palace of the Shirvanshahs

excerpt: Landmark pedestrian street lined with stately buildings, high-end fashion boutiques & embassies.
detail_description: Nizami St, located in the heart of Baku, is a bustling pedestrian street known for its elegant buildings, upscale fashion boutiques, and diplomatic missions. This central shopping district stretches along the Caspian Sea and showcases a mix of architectural styles, from 19th-century neo-renaissance to Socialist blocks. The area is also home to the vibrant Icherisheher (Old City) with its charming antique and souvenir shops.
name: Nizami St

detail_description: Fountains Square, located in the heart of Baku, has a rich history dating back to pre-revolutionary times when it was initially planned as a park. The square is adorned with numerous classic and modern fountains, making it a picturesque spot for visitors. It's also a shopper's paradise, featuring high-end fashion boutiques and stylish restaurants. Bookworms can explore the English language selection at Ali & Nino Bookstore or participate in their free book-swap shelf in the cafe.
name: Fountains Square

excerpt: Time-tested museum featuring a vast collection of unique miniature books from over 60 countries.
detail_description: Located in Baku, the Museum of Miniature Books is a unique and time-tested attraction that showcases an extensive collection of tiny books from over 60 countries. The museum, situated near the Palace of the Shirvanshahs, houses over 6,500 miniature books personally collected by Zarifa Salahova over three decades. Visitors can marvel at rare finds such as a miniature Quran and a Russian book that requires a magnifying glass to read.
name: Museum of Miniature Books

excerpt: Set on a hillside, this rare, natural gas fire blazes nonstop, with flames going 9+ ft. in the air.
detail_description: Yanar Dag, also known as the Burning Mountains, is a natural gas fire located on a hillside in Baku on the Absheron Peninsula by the Caspian Sea. The flames, which have been burning for over 4,000 years without stopping or spreading, can reach up to 9 feet in height and continue to burn regardless of weather conditions.
name: Yanar Dag

detail_description: Boulevard, also known as Seaside National Park, is a must-visit destination in Baku. Stretching along the Caspian Sea shore, this 5-kilometer-long promenade offers a refreshing sea breeze and stunning views of modern Baku's futuristic architecture. Lined with vibrant flowers and offering various activities such as cycling and enjoying attractions, it's a popular spot for locals and tourists alike.
name: Boulevard

excerpt: Ancient, castle-like temple complex once used as a Hindu & Zoroastrian place of worship.
detail_description: Atashgah Zoroastrian Fire Temple, located 21 km east of Baku, is an ancient complex that served as a place of worship for Hindus and Zoroastrians. Built in the 18th century by Indian merchants, it features a stoned-fenced courtyard and a Fireplace that ignites massive fires in the center and smaller ones on the rooftop corners.
name: Atashgah Zoroastrian Fire Temple

detail_description: Icherisheher, also known as the Old City, is a historic area in Baku that reflects the city's evolution through its diverse architecture. From the 12th-century walls surrounding the UNESCO World Heritage site to Soviet-era buildings and modern skyscrapers like the iconic Flame Towers, it showcases a range of influences. The Azerbaijan National Art Museum and Azerbaijan Carpet Museum display rich art and cultural traditions, including contemporary works.
name: Icherisheher

excerpt: Huge mosque opened in 2014, featuring domes with Koranic inscriptions, local stonework & 4 minarets.
detail_description: The Heydar Mosque, situated in the Binagadi district of Baku, is a significant religious symbol named after the esteemed former president of Azerbaijan, Heydar Aliyev. This grand architectural masterpiece was unveiled in 2014 and boasts traditional Azerbaijani and Islamic design elements alongside modern features.
name: Heydar Mosque

excerpt: Large state museum in a 19th-century mansion showcasing diverse historical objects & artifacts.
detail_description: The National Museum of History of Azerbaijan is housed in a grand 19th-century mansion originally built by Haji Zeynalabdin Tagiev, a prominent figure in Azerbaijani history. This historical landmark offers visitors a comprehensive look at the country's past through its diverse collection of artifacts and objects. Divided into three sections, the museum showcases everything from ancient coins and military items to prehistoric human bones and tombs.
name: National Museum of History of Azerbaijan
address: 4 Haji Zeynalabdin Taghiyev St, Baku 1005, Azerbaijan

detail_description: Flag Square, located in the capital city of Azerbaijan, Baku, is home to the national flag of the Republic of Azerbaijan. This significant landmark features a massive flag on a towering flagpole and is adorned with the Republic's emblem and a gilded bronze map of Azerbaijan. Situated near the Azerbaijan Navy base, it holds great importance for the country. The square officially opened in 2007 and serves as a symbol of national pride.
name: Flag square

detail_description: Old City Baku, also known as Icherisheher, is the oldest part of the city and a hub for characterful antiques and souvenir shops. Nizami Street in the city center is bustling with shopping and strolling opportunities, while traditional bazaars offer a local experience with fresh produce from the country's fertile regions. The area was confined within fortified walls until the mid-19th century and has been recognized as a UNESCO-listed site.
name: Old City Baku

excerpt: Elevated terrace reached by stairs or funicular ride, offering dramatic views of the city & sea.
detail_description: Highland Park, also known as Viewing Park, is a stunning destination in Baku, Azerbaijan. It features an elevated terrace that provides breathtaking views of the city and the sea. The park boasts a diverse collection of trees from around the world, making it an ideal spot for family outings or educational experiences. Visitors can explore the vast green spaces and leafy trees while taking in panoramic views of Baku's iconic landmarks such as Maiden Tower, Flame Towers, Flag Square, and more.
name: Highland Park

excerpt: Vast Ferris wheel-style attraction that's lit up at night, with panoramas of the city & Caspian Sea.
detail_description: The Baku Eye, also known as the Baku Ferris Wheel or Devil's Wheel, is a prominent attraction located in Baku's Seaside National Park. Originally built for the 2012 Eurovision Song Contest, it has become one of the city's top tourist spots. Visitors can enjoy breathtaking panoramic views of Baku and the Caspian Sea from air-conditioned capsules as they take a spin on this iconic landmark.
name: Baku Eye

excerpt: Baku, the capital and commercial hub of Azerbaijan, is a low-lying city with coastline along the Caspian Sea. It's famed for its medieval walled old city, which contains the Palace of the Shirvanshahs, a vast royal complex, and the iconic stone Maiden Tower. Contemporary landmarks include the Zaha Hadid–designed Heydar Aliyev Center, and the Flame Towers, 3 pointed skyscrapers covered with LED screens.
detail_description: Baku, the capital of Azerbaijan, is a vibrant city with a mix of medieval and contemporary landmarks. The old city boasts the Palace of the Shirvanshahs and the iconic Maiden Tower, while modern architecture includes the Zaha Hadid-designed Heydar Aliyev Center and the Flame Towers. A five-day tour offers a comprehensive experience, from exploring Baku's lively streets to venturing into nature in the Greater Caucasus.
name: Baku

excerpt: Museum of Azeri literature & culture featuring a vast collection of rare books & manuscripts.
detail_description: Nizami Museum of Azerbaijani Literature, located in the heart of Baku, is a cultural treasure showcasing a vast collection of rare books and manuscripts. The museum's magnificent building features blue majolica on its facade and monuments dedicated to six prominent figures in Azerbaijani literature. It serves as the main center for exploring Azerbaijan's rich literary heritage and history.
name: Nizami Museum of Azerbaijani Literature

detail_description: The Gobustan and Mud Volcanoes tour is a fascinating journey to explore the unique natural wonders of Azerbaijan. The mud volcanoes in this region are not your typical towering peaks, with some reaching only 2 meters in height. However, what makes them truly special is that nearly half of the world's mud volcanoes can be found here, including the tallest one at 1000 meters. These natural formations bubble with cold mud, offering a mesmerizing sight.
name: Gobustan & Mud Volcanoes tour
address: AHmad Rajably 209a, 3/31 MZ PLAZA, Bakı, Azerbaijan

excerpt: Lavish replica of a 13th-century mosque destroyed by Bolsheviks, with the tomb of Ukeyma Khanum.
detail_description: Bibiheybat Mosque is a stunning reconstruction of a 13th-century mosque that was destroyed during the Soviet era. Situated near Baku bay, it offers breathtaking views of the Caspian shipyard and Bibiheybat oilfields. The complex also houses the tomb of Ukeyma Khanum. Visitors can explore its beautiful Islamic architecture and interior, but it's best to plan visits between 9-11am or 2-4pm to avoid prayer times.
name: Bibiheybat Mosque

detail_description: The Juma Mosque, located in the old town of IcheriSheher in Baku, is a stunning example of oriental mosque architecture from the 12th century. The facade features intricate wooden and stone patterns, while the interior is adorned with tiled stones and ancient inscriptions from the Koran in Arabic script. This historical site offers visitors a glimpse into Azerbaijan's medieval architectural heritage.
name: Juma Mosque

detail_description: Ateshgah Insurance Group offers a variety of travel insurances that are ideal for a group of individuals seeking coverage for their trip. Their online platform provides convenience and ease in purchasing the necessary policies. The company's team efficiently and accurately addresses all inquiries received through Whatsapp, ensuring prompt responses to any questions.
name: Ateshgah Insurance Group

detail_description: Yashil Bazaar, also known as the Green Bazaar, is a popular market in Baku where visitors can immerse themselves in an authentic Azerbaijani experience. Located a little away from the city center, this bustling street market offers a wide variety of fresh fruits, organic herbs, colorful spices, and local delicacies like saffron and caviar. Visitors can sample flavorful teas and traditional Azeri snacks and sweets before deciding on purchases.
name: Yashil bazaar

detail_description: Yaşıl Bazar, also known as the Green Bazaar, is a bustling market located northeast of the Old City in Baku. It's a popular spot for locals to shop for groceries and pick up souvenirs. The main hall offers an array of dried fruits and preserved grape leaves, while boutique shops specialize in local saffron, honey, and caviar from Azerbaijan sturgeon.
name: Yaşıl Bazar

detail_description: Mini-Venice, located near the Carpet Museum in Baku, is a charming canal system that offers visitors a taste of Venice. The area features several islands connected by bridges and offers gondola rides through its artificial canals. With replicas of the Bridge of Sighs and a tunnel to pass through, it provides picturesque views and is perfect for a romantic evening stroll.
name: Mini Venice

excerpt: Museum devoted to contemporary Azeri art, along with works by Dalí, Picasso & Chagall.
detail_description: The Museum of Modern Art, established in 2009, is one of the newest cultural institutions in Azerbaijan. It showcases contemporary Azeri art as well as works by renowned artists such as Dalí, Picasso, and Chagall. The museum's building itself is a work of art with its innovative design that emphasizes open spaces and unique architectural elements.
name: Museum of Modern Art

detail_description: Mud Volcano, located about 15 kilometers north of downtown Baku, is a unique natural attraction in the Baku Region. Despite not having active mud vents, it offers an apocalyptic photo scenery due to the waste from neighboring communities. The area features Toragay, the world's highest mud volcano at an altitude of 402 meters above sea level.
name: Mud Volcano

detail_description: The Funicular Baku, established in 1960 during the Soviet era, is a unique transportation experience in Azerbaijan. It is the country's first and only funicular, offering a quick journey from Neftchilar Avenue to Martyrs Alley. The ride provides stunning panoramic views of Baku, including the iconic Flame Towers. While the train ride takes only 4 to 5 minutes, some visitors recommend taking the adjacent stairs for an even more breathtaking view of the city's coastline.
name: Funicular Baku

detail_description: Baku City Seaside National Park is a captivating attraction featuring diverse plant species. Visitors can enjoy leisurely strolls through expansive green spaces and lush tree-lined paths, making it an ideal spot for families. The park offers numerous seating areas and tranquil water ponds, providing ample opportunities for relaxation and enjoyment.
name: Baku City Seaside National Park

excerpt: Cemetery & memorial for those killed by the Soviet Army in Black January & the Nagorno-Karabakh War.
detail_description: Martyrs' Lane, located in Baku, is a poignant cemetery and memorial honoring the memory of around 15,000 Azerbaijani individuals who perished during the Black January massacre and the Nagorno-Karabakh War. This site was constructed on the grounds of a former cemetery that was demolished during the Bolshevik era. The central feature of Martyrs' Lane is an Eternal Flame, and visitors often leave fresh wreaths to pay their respects.
name: Martyrs' Lane

excerpt: Park & promenade featuring waterfront recreation areas plus museums, restaurants, shopping & more.
detail_description: Dənizkənarı Milli Park, also known as The Boulevard, is a historic promenade along the Caspian Sea in Baku. It dates back over 100 years and was once home to the mansions of oil barons. Today, it offers a variety of recreational activities such as open-air and 5D cinemas, a 197-foot Ferris wheel, museums, restaurants, shopping areas, and more.
name: Baku Boulevard

detail_description: The Absheron Peninsula, located east of Baku and extending into the Caspian Sea, offers a variety of geological wonders, including a flaming hillside. For those interested in textiles and handicrafts, a visit to the town of Quba is recommended. This little town is home to one of Azerbaijan's seven schools of carpet weaving, with several workshops where visitors can observe master weavers at work.
name: Absheron peninsula

excerpt: Constructed in the early 1900s, this landmark mosque offers ornate architecture & prayer services.
detail_description: Təzə Pir Mosque, built in the early 1900s, stands on a site that once served as a sanctuary from the 15th century. Despite not being an extraordinary mosque, it offers insight into Azerbaijani men's worship and faith in Islam. A 20-minute walk from the Old City takes you to this peaceful hilltop mosque with authentic surroundings.
name: Təzəpir məscidi

excerpt: Established in 1936, this art museum features works by Azeri & international artists.
detail_description: The Azerbaijan State Museum of Art, established in 1936, showcases an extensive collection of Azeri and international art. With over 60 rooms filled with about 20% of its vast collection on display at any given time, the museum offers a diverse range of artworks. Visitors can explore European art alongside masterpieces from artists across the Caucasus, Central Asia, China, and Japan. It's a must-visit destination for art enthusiasts looking to immerse themselves in a rich cultural experience.
name: Azerbaijan State Museum of Art

detail_description: Baku State Philharmonic Hall, also known as Magomayev Azerbaijan State Philharmonic Hall, is a renowned cultural center in Baku. Built in 1912 with stunning Italian Renaissance and German Rococo architectural styles, it hosts regular classical and traditional concerts in a spectacular early-20th century rotunda. The venue offers nice acoustics, affordable ticket prices, and comfortable seating.
name: Baku State Philharmonic Hall

detail_description: Baku Promenade, also known as Baku Boulevard, is a 4-km long walkway along the Caspian Sea coast, offering stunning views and modern attractions. It stretches from the House of Government to the Carpet Museum and features iconic landmarks such as the Flaming Towers and Caspian Waterfront Mall. The promenade is lined with vibrant seaside venues, including malls, museums, theaters, playgrounds, flag poles, ferris wheels, restaurants and cafes.
name: Baku Promenade

excerpt: Government-run zoo since 1928, with around 160 different species displayed across several acres.
detail_description: Baku Zoological Park, established by the government in 1928, is home to approximately 160 different species spread across vast acres. The park offers a panoramic view of Baku from Upland Park Noble 3 Flaming Towers, known for its stunning lighting and LED screens. Visitors can also explore the historic Old City, Icheri Sheher, which features the ancient Maiden Tower and Shirvanshah palace.
name: Baku Zoological Park

detail_description: Muhammad Mosque, also known as Siniggala Mosque, is a significant symbol of Baku, dating back to the 11th century. Despite not being the largest or most grandiose mosque in the city, it holds historical importance. The minaret bears witness to the Russo-Persian War and remains unrepaired as a testament to Baku's resilience. This 1000-year-old mosque has been meticulously preserved and now serves as a Quran museum.
name: Muhammad Mosque

detail_description: In the heart of Baku, Azerbaijan, lies the historic Maiden Tower, a 15th-century structure that offers panoramic views of the city from its 29-meter-high terrace. This UNESCO World Heritage Site is steeped in myths and legends, including a tale about a shah's daughter who leaped into the Caspian Sea to escape an unwanted marriage. Nearby, visitors can explore the Palace of Shirvanshahs, a beautifully restored 15th-century palace complex.
name: Maiden Tower

detail_description: Baku Old City, also known as Icheri Sheher, is a historic walled city dating back to the 12th to 16th centuries. The sandstone walls are adorned with low turrets and defensive structures, showcasing its role in protecting the city from invaders. Designated as a UNESCO site, it boasts rich cultural heritage and intricate decorations reflecting various eras of life. Visitors can explore its charming streets and enjoy diverse dining options within this ancient enclave.
name: Old City

detail_description: Small Caravanserai is a historical site that served as a resting place for travelers and their animals along trade routes in the Middle East and Central Asia. Divided into open and closed types, it offers an immersive experience of past centuries. The beautifully restored location now operates as a restaurant with attentive staff, making it a great stop for visitors.
name: Small Caravanserai

detail_description: GREEN STORE MARKET is a well-known local market in Baku, offering a wide variety of fresh fruits, vegetables, dairy products, and meats. It is popular for its affordable prices compared to supermarkets in the area. Visitors can also enjoy haggling for the best deals on their purchases.
name: GREEN STORE MARKET
address: EHMED, Əhməd Mehbalıyev küç, Bakı 1047, Azerbaijan

detail_description: Bulvar is a lively and bustling promenade located in the heart of the city. It is known for its vibrant atmosphere, lined with an array of shops, restaurants, and entertainment options. Visitors can enjoy leisurely strolls along the Bulvar, taking in the sights and sounds of the bustling street. The area is popular among both locals and tourists alike, offering a diverse range of activities and attractions to suit all interests.
name: Bulvar

excerpt: Elevated terrace reached by stairs or funicular ride, offering dramatic views of the city & sea.
detail_description: Upland Park, also known as Dagustu Park, is a hilltop park located in the topmost region of Baku. It offers stunning panoramic views of the city's skyline and the Caspian Sea. The park features a war memorial, fountain, and a viewing deck that overlooks the Baku waterfront. One of its main attractions is the breathtaking view of the city lights twinkling below at night.
name: Highland Park

detail_description: Located in Baku, Azerbaijan, the YARAT Contemporary Art Centre is a non-profit organization founded by artist Aida Mahmudova in 2011. The center aims to be a hub for artistic practice, research, thinking and education in Azerbaijan. It features temporary exhibitions by international artists and showcases emerging movements and new commissions. The venue also houses displays from the YARAT Collection.
name: YARAT Contemporary Art Centre

detail_description: Baku Olympic Stadium, situated on the scenic Lake Beyuk Shor, is a modern sports venue with a capacity of nearly 70,000 spectators. It hosts various national and international events, including the opening and closing ceremonies of the first European Games in 2015. The stadium boasts state-of-the-art facilities and infrastructure such as ample parking space, parks, boulevards, and numerous indoor and outdoor amenities for diverse activities.
name: Baku Stadium

detail_description: The Azerbaijan State Academic Russian Drama Theatre, established in 1920, is a historic theater in Baku that offers captivating performances of classic Russian and Soviet literature as well as entertaining children's plays. The cozy venue provides an engaging experience with reasonable ticket prices. While the sound quality may not be perfect, the talented actors make the shows thoroughly enjoyable.
name: Azerbaijan State Academic Russian Drama Theater

excerpt: Multi-story shopping mall with an international food court & a roof terrace with bay views.
detail_description: Park Bulvar Mall is a multi-story shopping center located in Baku Boulevard, offering stunning bay views from its roof terrace. It opened in 2010 and has become a popular destination for both locals and tourists. The mall features international brands, an enticing food court, and entertainment options such as a cinema and bowling alley.
name: Park Bulvar Mall
